body:
There's also a seemingly innocent usage that would break if we made it scope based:

```powershell
$arrays = [int[][]]::new(3)
$arrays[0] = 0..2
$arrays[1] = 3..6
$arrays[2] = 7..9

foreach ($array in $arrays) {
    $array | ForEach-Object {
        if ($_ -eq 3) {
            # skip the rest of this array
            continue
        }

        $_
    }
}
```

Pretty contrived example, but most folks won't understand why that isn't valid. I'm all for a PSSA rule telling folks to not to do this. Whether we like it or not though, this use case seems pretty specifically designed for.  If this *happened* to work because of an implementation detail that'd be one thing, but PowerShell basically told folks this is okay to do 🤷

I've got a few notes about this topic:

1. [This has come up over on the Pester project as well.](https://github.com/pester/Pester/issues/412)  
2. This is also the topic of #5811.
3. Unlabeled `break` and `continue` are "catchable" without escaping a PowerShell.  I've been using a test fixture to trap on functions that "throw" `break`s and `continue`s.  See below.
4. `break $label` and `continue $label` ~~do not seem to be catchable if you don't know $label _a priori_.~~ seem to be catchable only by catching them at a PowerShell boundary [per @SeeminglyScience's comment below](https://github.com/PowerShell/PowerShell/issues/12742#issuecomment-632162877).

<details>
<summary> code that catches `break` and `continue`</summary>

```PowerShell
function Invoke-Loop
{
    param
    (
        [Parameter(Position=1,Mandatory)]
        [scriptblock]
        $ScriptBlock,

        [Parameter(Mandatory)]
        [Assuage.Fixtures.Pipeline.LoopBreakResult]
        [Alias('result')]
        $BreakResultOutput
    )
    $usual = $false
    $continued = $false
    $i = 0
    do {
        if ($i -ge 1)
        {
            $i++

            if ( -not $usual )
            {
                $continued = $true
            }
        }
        else
        {
            $i++

            % $ScriptBlock

            $usual = $true
        }
    } while ($i -le 1)

    if ( $usual )
    {
        $BreakResultOutput.SetResult([Assuage.Fixtures.Pipeline.LoopBreakOccurrence]::DidNotBreak)
        return
    }
    if ( $continued )
    {
        $BreakResultOutput.SetResult([Assuage.Fixtures.Pipeline.LoopBreakOccurrence]::Continued)
        return
    }
    $BreakResultOutput.SetResult([Assuage.Fixtures.Pipeline.LoopBreakOccurrence]::Broke)
}
```
</details>

@alx9r You can catch them a little easier like this:

```powershell
$sb = { break }
$ps = $null
try {
    $ps = [powershell]::Create('CurrentRunspace')
    $settings = [System.Management.Automation.PSInvocationSettings]@{
        ExposeFlowControlExceptions = $true
    }

    $ps.AddScript('. $args[0]', $false).
        AddArgument($sb).
        Invoke($null, $settings)

} catch [System.Management.Automation.FlowControlException] {
    $PSItem.Exception.GetType().FullName
} finally {
    if ($null -ne $ps) {
        $ps.Dispose()
    }
}
```

which returns:

```
System.Management.Automation.BreakException
```

Note that I have seen folks who only ever write "controller" style scripts use `break` to exit early.  I've also seen those folks use a pattern like this:

```powershell
try {
    # Entire script here
} catch {
    continue
}
```

They put `continue` in the catch block because PSSA warns them about an empty catch block, and because nothing comes after the catch it *appears* to work.

I know this is pretty much the exact scenario we want to stop, but even throwing if the flow control exception reaches `Executor` will break production scripts (well, it wouldn't change behavior but would report as failed).
